As everyone who has written a C program of sufficient complexity knows, these warnings are <i>not</i> always correct.  Google for "spurious warnings uninitialized", e.g:<p><a href="http://kerneltrap.org/node/6591" rel="nofollow">http://kerneltrap.org/node/6591</a><p>An unrelated example where gcc (and icc) emit needless warnings about integer types is this:<p><pre><code>  int x = foo();
  unsigned y = (x == 0);

</code></pre>
Don't get me wrong, I'm in favor of cranking up the warning levels, but there is a reason why not everything is included in -Wall (yes, "uninitialized" is included, I know).
